Import Phylogenetic Tree

Tree is a consensus tree built in Mesquite from 10k Trees grafted with fossil taxa.

# read tree in NEX format from wd into R environment 
tree<-read.nexus("navicular_tree.nex")

# extract species from data 
spp_obs <- as.character(d$Taxon)

# trim imported tree to the species in data 
tree_trimmed <- keep.tip(tree,spp_obs)

Data Wrangling

Many of the functions require named lists of numbers instead of data frames, so we have to make these.

# reorder data frame by tip labels in the tree
reorder_d<-ReorderData(tree_trimmed,d,1) # number is the column with species names 

# crop data sheet to species with values for all variables 
c_reorder_d<-reorder_d[complete.cases(reorder_d),]
c_spp_obs<-as.character(c_reorder_d$Taxon)
# trim tree to species with values for all variables 
c_tree_trimmed<-keep.tip(tree_trimmed,c_spp_obs)

# make data object for entocuneiform facet area/astragular facet area
ent_ast<-c_reorder_d[,"ent_ast"]
names(ent_ast)<-c_reorder_d$Taxon

# make data object for (ectocuneiform facet area+mesocuneiform)/astragular facet area
ectmes_ast<-c_reorder_d[,"ectmes_ast"]
names(ectmes_ast)<-c_reorder_d$Taxon

Ancestral State Reconstruction using fastAnc function


Estimates ancestral states for a continuous character under maximum likelihood (choses the parameters of a statistical model to provide the most probable description of the observed data). The function reroots the tree at all internal nodes and computes the contrasts state at the root each time.

The output is a list (names are node numbers) with the reconstructed values at internal nodes (ace), variances on the estimates (var), and/or 95-percent confidence intervals (CI95).

# Ancestral Character Estimates using fastAnc() which produces an object with estimated values at ancestral nodes with 95% CI
anc_ent_ast<-fastAnc(c_tree_trimmed,ent_ast,var=TRUE,CI=TRUE) # Entocuneiform facet area as a ratio of astragalar facet area
print(anc_ent_ast) # shows list of ace numbered by node and a list of 95% CI of each estimate numbered by node

Visualizing Ancestral State Reconstruction for a Continuous Trait


This is a method that is a quick, easy way to plot the ASR of a continuous trait throughout a phylogeny. Under the hood, the continuous mapping function is using the fastAnc method from the previous chunk.

# make object that projects the reconstruction onto the edges of the tree 
map.obj<-contMap(c_tree_trimmed,ent_ast,plot = FALSE)

# plot ASR of the ratio of entocuneiform facet area to astragalar facet area 
plot(map.obj,type="phylogram",sig=2,outline=FALSE) # to 2 significant digits


Ancestral State Reconstruction using anc.Bayes function

Uses Bayesian MCMC to sample from the posterior distribution for the states at internal nodes in the tree.

Can assign a starting value for the BM rate as a prior, but this ist required.

Can assign a value for the root and/or specific nodes as a prior, but this isnt required.

After running the ASR (which takes some time), the output can be saved to the working directory as an RDS file and imported during later sessions. Having saved the RDS will prevent always needing to run the ASR MCMC and also helps with reproducibility.

set.seed(23)
# run MCMC; should use at least 1e6 generations 
ace_ent_ast<-anc.Bayes(c_tree_trimmed,ent_ast,ngen=1e6) 

# save MCMC output to the wd as an RDS file 
saveRDS(ace_ent_ast, "ace_ent_ast.rds")
# load in Bayes models after they've been ran and saved
ace_ent_ast <- readRDS("ace_ent_ast.rds") 

# returns vector of estimated ancestral states with default burn-in of 20% of MCMC generations
summary(ace_ent_ast)

The base R function, density(), can be used to make a object that describes the posterior distribution of the ASR by the anc.Bayes MCMC.

# compare posterior density of the estimates of entocuneiform facet area / astragular facet area at specific nodes of interest

dens_115<-density(ace_ent_ast,what=115,burnin=20000) # number of node indicated with the "what=" command

Phylogenetic Signal of a Trait Using phylosig function

The phylosig function calculates the phylogenetic signal of a trait using two different, user-specified methods:

  1. \(\lambda\) per Pagel, 1998
  2. K per Bloomberg et al., 2003.

This function can also indicate whether a phylogenetic signal by either method is significant (p<0.05).


1. Pagels \(\lambda\) Method

Output is \(\lambda\) value and the p-value of the estimated phylogenetic signal tested against null hypothesis.

\(\lambda\) values range between 0 and the thereotical upper limit of \(\lambda\) determined by the relative height of the most recent internal node.

# Pagel's Method
y_lambda<-phylosig(c_tree_trimmed,ectmes_ast,method="lambda",test=TRUE)
# Returns lambda and P-value against null hypothesis 
print(y_lambda) 

Phylogenetic signal lambda : 0.91643 
logL(lambda) : 167.925 
LR(lambda=0) : 70.1842 
P-value (based on LR test) : 5.40184e-17



The returned phylosig object can then be used to visualize the \(\lambda\) likelihood surface.

# Plots likelihood surface 
plot(y_lambda) 
title(main="ecto. facet area + meso. facet area / ast. facet area")

2. Bloombergs K Method

Output is K and p-value of K against null hypothesis.

# Bloomberg et al.'s Method
y_K<-phylosig(c_tree_trimmed,ectmes_ast,method="K",test=TRUE)
# Returns K and P-value of test against null hypothesis 
print(y_K)

Phylogenetic signal K : 0.415063 
P-value (based on 1000 randomizations) : 0.001 
# Using returned phylosig obj to plot observed value of K and the null distribution of K
plot(y_K)
title(main="ectocuneiform facet area + mesocuneiform facet area / astragular facet area")


Test for an Evolutionary Trend Using phytools ACE Model Comparison


This method only tests across the entire tree.This method relies on phytools, the package that been used for most of the analyses so far. However, models may not converge, so this method should be used with caution.

# ent_ast

# fit with no trend model
fit.bm.entast<-anc.ML(c_tree_trimmed,ent_ast,model="BM")

# fit with trend model
fit.trend.entast<-anc.trend(c_tree_trimmed,ent_ast) # Note that this will generally only work and produce sensible results for a phylogeny with some  fossil species

# compare trend vs no trend models and estimates
AIC(fit.bm.entast,fit.trend.entast)
                  df       AIC
fit.bm.entast    109 -674.9828
fit.trend.entast 110 2934.5659
# fit with no trend model
fit.bm.ectmesast<-anc.ML(c_tree_trimmed,ectmes_ast,model="BM")
 
# fit with trend model
fit.trend.ectmesast<-anc.trend(c_tree_trimmed,ectmes_ast)


# compare trend vs no trend models and estimates
AIC(fit.bm.ectmesast,fit.trend.ectmesast)


Test for Trends in Rate and Phenotypic Change using Phylogenetic Ridge Regression


Unlike other Phylogenetic Comparative Methods, RRPhylo can test for trends across the entire tree and within specific lineages. Analyses can be informed with fossil taxa.

To search for temporal trends in phenotypes and absolute rates, the function computes regression slopes between values at nodes and tips and their distance from the root. Absolute rates are rescaled from 0-1 and logged. Significance is determed by comparing the real slope to a family of 100 slopes generated by simulating phenotypes under Brownian Motion.

# whole tree 
RR<-RRphylo(tree=c_tree_trimmed,y=ent_ast)
search.trend(RR=RR,y=ent_ast)
# At specific nodes (base of Euprimates = 115, base of Strepsirrhines = 175)
search.trend(RR=RR,y=ent_ast,node = c(115,175))

Example RRphylo plots for node 175

First, make an object to be passed to plotting functions for a node of interest. Here, node 175 is the base of Strepsirrhines.

plotST175<-plotTrend(search.trend(RR=RR,y=ent_ast,node = 175))

Plot the phenotypic change through time (left), and the rate of evolutionary change through time (right) of the ratio of entocuneiform facet area to astragular facet area. These plots compare the actual values for the whole tree against the expectations of change according to brownian motion.

plotST175$plotPhen(1) # to plot phenotypic trend through time for entire tree
plotST175$plotRates(1) # to plot rates trend through time for entire tree

Plot the phenotypic change through time (left), and the rate of evolutionary change through time (right) of the ratio of entocuneiform facet area to astragular facet area. These plots compare the clade descended from node 175 against the rest of the tree.

plotST175$plotPhenNode("y") # to plot phenotypic trend through time for the clade
plotST175$plotRatesNode("y") # to plot rates trend through time for the clade

Multivariate Evolutionary Model Comparison using mvMORPH

Fit different evolutionary models to data across the entire tree using the functions from mvMORPH package.

The models are then compared using Akaike Information Criterion (AIC) weights.


Fit Brownian Motion Model with No Trend

# Brownian Motion with no trend 
fit_bm<-mvBM(c_tree_trimmed,ent_ast,model = "BM1",diagnostic = F)


Fit Brownian Motion Model with Trend

Note: according to mvMORPH documentation, a trend can be estimated reliably only on non-ultrametric trees, so first check the tree if youre not sure.

is.ultrametric(c_tree_trimmed) # according to mvMORPH documentation, a trend can be estimated reliably only on non-ultrametric trees.
# Brownian Motion with trend
fit_bm_t<-mvBM(c_tree_trimmed,ent_ast,param=list(trend=TRUE),model = "BM1",diagnostic = F)


Fit Early Burst Model (Harmon et al.2010)

# Fit Early Burst Model (Harmon et al. 2010)
fit_EB<-mvEB(c_tree_trimmed,ent_ast,method="sparse")


Fit Model According to Ornstein-Uhlenbeck Process with unique selective regime for the whole tree

# Fit model according to Ornstein-Uhlenbeck process with unique selective regime for the whole tree 
fit_OU<-mvOU(c_tree_trimmed,ent_ast,model="OU1",method="sparse")


Compare Evolutionary Models using AICc

AICc is Aaike Information Criterion with a correction for small sample sizes.

# Compare AIC 
results<-c(AIC(fit_bm),AIC(fit_bm_t),AIC(fit_EB),AIC(fit_OU))
aicw(results,aicc=TRUE) # AICc is AIC with correction for small sample sizes
